<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1618,2042]" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,455,1907,1933]" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">External morphology.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[460,663,1908,1933]" class="Demospongiae" family="Acarnidae" genus="Iophon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="11" pageNumber="472" phylum="Porifera" rank="subSpecies" species="situ" subSpecies="appearance">
<emphasis box="[460,663,1908,1933]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">In situ appearance</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[676,790,1906,1933]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1235,1260]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,481,1215]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,481,1215]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 5. Iophon unicorne Topsent, 1907 BELUM.Mc2015.771. A. In situ appearance. B. Skeleton, scale bar 1000 µm. C. Style. D. Style ends. E. Tylote. F. Tylote ends. G. Chelae. Spicule scale bars all 10 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3376040/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="472">Figure 5A</figureCitation>
): A yellow encrusting sponge.All but one of our specimens had thin branchlets arising from their surface, as the basal crust was often obscured by algae this gave the impression of a stalked branched sponge. The individual projections were thin (around 
<quantity box="[986,1063,1979,2006]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="472" unit="mm" value="20.0">20 mm</quantity>
maximum diameter), translucent, up to 
<quantity box="[214,289,2014,2042]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="11" pageNumber="472" unit="cm" value="1.5">1.5 cm</quantity>
in length, and had rounded ends, although in some cases the branchlets rejoined the sponge surface.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,153,467]" box="[199,1060,153,179]" pageId="12" pageNumber="473">
<emphasis box="[199,458,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="473">Preserved appearance.</emphasis>
Dark yellow branchlets or crust with smooth surface.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,153,467]" pageId="12" pageNumber="473">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,302,188,215]" pageId="12" pageNumber="473">Skeleton</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[317,434,188,215]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1235,1260]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,481,1215]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,481,1215]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 5. Iophon unicorne Topsent, 1907 BELUM.Mc2015.771. A. In situ appearance. B. Skeleton, scale bar 1000 µm. C. Style. D. Style ends. E. Tylote. F. Tylote ends. G. Chelae. Spicule scale bars all 10 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3376040/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="473">Figure 5B</figureCitation>
): Ascending bundles of up to 10 styles irregularly anastomising, joined by 1–2 spicules. Ectosomal fans of tylotes. Microscleres scattered throughout tissue.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,153,467]" box="[199,801,260,287]" pageId="12" pageNumber="473">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,307,260,287]" pageId="12" pageNumber="473">Spicules:</emphasis>
Measurements from 
<collectionCode box="[545,646,260,287]" country="United Kingdom" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/2x42-q9ch" name="Ulster Museum, Belfast" pageId="12" pageNumber="473">BELUM</collectionCode>
.Mc2015.646:
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,153,467]" pageId="12" pageNumber="473">
Styles (
<figureCitation box="[281,431,296,323]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1235,1260]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,481,1215]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,481,1215]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 5. Iophon unicorne Topsent, 1907 BELUM.Mc2015.771. A. In situ appearance. B. Skeleton, scale bar 1000 µm. C. Style. D. Style ends. E. Tylote. F. Tylote ends. G. Chelae. Spicule scale bars all 10 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3376040/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="473">Figure 5C, D</figureCitation>
): 389(418)446 by 13(16) 
<quantity box="[706,783,297,324]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="473" unit="mm" value="20.0">20 µm</quantity>
. Curved styles with an abrupt point and a large single spine on the basal end.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,153,467]" pageId="12" pageNumber="473">
Tylotes (
<figureCitation box="[295,411,368,395]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1235,1260]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,481,1215]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,481,1215]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 5. Iophon unicorne Topsent, 1907 BELUM.Mc2015.771. A. In situ appearance. B. Skeleton, scale bar 1000 µm. C. Style. D. Style ends. E. Tylote. F. Tylote ends. G. Chelae. Spicule scale bars all 10 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3376040/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="473">Figure 5E</figureCitation>
): 208(223)242 by 7(10) 
<quantity box="[675,745,369,395]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="12" pageNumber="473" unit="mm" value="11.0">11 µm</quantity>
Ends slightly swollen but not rounded and spined with several spines in a flattened crown (
<figureCitation box="[466,581,404,431]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1235,1260]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,481,1215]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,481,1215]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 5. Iophon unicorne Topsent, 1907 BELUM.Mc2015.771. A. In situ appearance. B. Skeleton, scale bar 1000 µm. C. Style. D. Style ends. E. Tylote. F. Tylote ends. G. Chelae. Spicule scale bars all 10 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3376040/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="473">Figure 5F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,153,467]" box="[199,810,440,467]" pageId="12" pageNumber="473">
Chelae (
<figureCitation box="[291,412,440,467]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1235,1260]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,481,1215]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,481,1215]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 5. Iophon unicorne Topsent, 1907 BELUM.Mc2015.771. A. In situ appearance. B. Skeleton, scale bar 1000 µm. C. Style. D. Style ends. E. Tylote. F. Tylote ends. G. Chelae. Spicule scale bars all 10 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3376040/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="473">Figure 5G</figureCitation>
): 17(20) 
<quantity box="[504,582,441,467]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="12" pageNumber="473" unit="mm" value="24.0">24 µm</quantity>
. Have a basal spine.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3376040/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="473" startId="12.[151,250,1235,1260]" targetBox="[151,1436,481,1215]" targetPageId="12">
